{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603126"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:32:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:32:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15716"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15716"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.02,0.05,0.05,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8407"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71477"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8407"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56986"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8397"},{"type":"tags","id":"8501"},{"type":"tags","id":"8502"},{"type":"tags","id":"10602"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20253"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71477"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA histological section of ovarian tissue from a 35-year-old woman shows a dense, collagenous structure in the cortex. The structure appears white macroscopically and contains hyalinised connective tissue with few cells. There is no evidence of active hormone production.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely being observed?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Corpus albicans","Corpus luteum","Corpus hemorrhagicum","Graafian follicle","Atretic follicle"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe description matches a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorpus albicans\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the final stage in corpus luteum regression. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorpus luteum\u003C/strong\u003E is yellowish in colour, would show large luteinised granulosa cells and active hormone production. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorpus hemorrhagicum\u003C/strong\u003E forms immediately after ovulation and contains blood. A \u003Cstrong\u003EGraafian follicle\u003C/strong\u003E is a mature ovarian follicle containing follicular fluid and an oocyte. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eatretic follicle\u003C/strong\u003E shows degenerating granulosa cells and a collapsed appearance but lacks the dense collagenous structure seen in a corpus albicans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe corpus albicans appears as a white, hyalinised scar composed mainly of collagen. It represents the final stage of corpus luteum degeneration after progesterone production has ceased. Multiple corpora albicantia can be found in the ovarian cortex as evidence of previous ovulations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The corpus albicans is the final stage in the regression of the corpus luteum, appearing as a white, fibrous scar in the ovarian cortex.","The corpus albicans forms after progesterone production ceases and the corpus luteum degenerates.","Multiple corpora albicantia accumulate in the ovarian cortex throughout reproductive life as evidence of past ovulations."],"references":["Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Fortune JE, Yang MY, Muruvi W. The earliest stages of follicular development: follicle formation 